INSERT INTO notes (parent, permanent, expanded, created, icons, title, text) VALUES (104, 0, 1, '2008-11-27 16:27:02', 0, N'Chapter 1', N'It is a truth universally acknowledged, that a single man in possession' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'of a good fortune, must be in want of a wife.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'However little known the feelings or views of such a man may be on his' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'first entering a neighbourhood, this truth is so well fixed in the minds' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'of the surrounding families, that he is considered the rightful property' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'of some one or other of their daughters.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"My dear Mr. Bennet," said his lady to him one day, "have you heard that' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Netherfield Park is let at last?"' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mr. Bennet replied that he had not.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"But it is," returned she; "for Mrs. Long has just been here, and she' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'told me all about it."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mr. Bennet made no answer.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Do you not want to know who has taken it?" cried his wife impatiently.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"_You_ want to tell me, and I have no objection to hearing it."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'This was invitation enough.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Why, my dear, you must know, Mrs. Long says that Netherfield is taken' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'by a young man of large fortune from the north of England; that he came' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'down on Monday in a chaise and four to see the place, and was so much' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'delighted with it, that he agreed with Mr. Morris immediately; that he' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'is to take possession before Michaelmas, and some of his servants are to' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'be in the house by the end of next week."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"What is his name?"' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Bingley."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Is he married or single?"' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Oh! Single, my dear, to be sure! A single man of large fortune; four or' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'five thousand a year. What a fine thing for our girls!"' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"How so? How can it affect them?"' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"My dear Mr. Bennet," replied his wife, "how can you be so tiresome! You' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'must know that I am thinking of his marrying one of them."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Is that his design in settling here?"' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Design! Nonsense, how can you talk so! But it is very likely that he' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'_may_ fall in love with one of them, and therefore you must visit him as' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'soon as he comes."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"I see no occasion for that. You and the girls may go, or you may send' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'them by themselves, which perhaps will be still better, for as you are' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'as handsome as any of them, Mr. Bingley may like you the best of the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'party."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"My dear, you flatter me. I certainly _have_ had my share of beauty, but' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'I do not pretend to be anything extraordinary now. When a woman has five' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'grown-up daughters, she ought to give over thinking of her own beauty."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"In such cases, a woman has not often much beauty to think of."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"But, my dear, you must indeed go and see Mr. Bingley when he comes into' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'the neighbourhood."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"It is more than I engage for, I assure you."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"But consider your daughters. Only think what an establishment it would' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'be for one of them. Sir William and Lady Lucas are determined to' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'go, merely on that account, for in general, you know, they visit no' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'newcomers. Indeed you must go, for it will be impossible for _us_ to' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'visit him if you do not."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"You are over-scrupulous, surely. I dare say Mr. Bingley will be very' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'glad to see you; and I will send a few lines by you to assure him of my' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'hearty consent to his marrying whichever he chooses of the girls; though' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'I must throw in a good word for my little Lizzy."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"I desire you will do no such thing. Lizzy is not a bit better than the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'others; and I am sure she is not half so handsome as Jane, nor half so' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'good-humoured as Lydia. But you are always giving _her_ the preference."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"They have none of them much to recommend them," replied he; "they are' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'all silly and ignorant like other girls; but Lizzy has something more of' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'quickness than her sisters."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Mr. Bennet, how _can_ you abuse your own children in such a way? You' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'take delight in vexing me. You have no compassion for my poor nerves."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"You mistake me, my dear. I have a high respect for your nerves. They' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'are my old friends. I have heard you mention them with consideration' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'these last twenty years at least."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Ah, you do not know what I suffer."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"But I hope you will get over it, and live to see many young men of four' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'thousand a year come into the neighbourhood."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"It will be no use to us, if twenty such should come, since you will not' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'visit them."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Depend upon it, my dear, that when there are twenty, I will visit them' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'all."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mr. Bennet was so odd a mixture of quick parts, sarcastic humour,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'reserve, and caprice, that the experience of three-and-twenty years had' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'been insufficient to make his wife understand his character. _Her_ mind' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'was less difficult to develop. She was a woman of mean understanding,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'little information, and uncertain temper. When she was discontented,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'she fancied herself nervous. The business of her life was to get her' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'daughters married; its solace was visiting and news.');
INSERT INTO notes (parent, permanent, expanded, created, icons, title, text) VALUES (104, 0, 1, '2008-11-27 16:29:16', 0, N'Chapter 2', N'Mr. Bennet was among the earliest of those who waited on Mr. Bingley. He' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'had always intended to visit him, though to the last always assuring' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'his wife that he should not go; and till the evening after the visit was' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'paid she had no knowledge of it. It was then disclosed in the following' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'manner. Observing his second daughter employed in trimming a hat, he' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'suddenly addressed her with:' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"I hope Mr. Bingley will like it, Lizzy."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"We are not in a way to know _what_ Mr. Bingley likes," said her mother' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'resentfully, "since we are not to visit."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"But you forget, mamma," said Elizabeth, "that we shall meet him at the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'assemblies, and that Mrs. Long promised to introduce him."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"I do not believe Mrs. Long will do any such thing. She has two nieces' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'of her own. She is a selfish, hypocritical woman, and I have no opinion' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'of her."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"No more have I," said Mr. Bennet; "and I am glad to find that you do' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'not depend on her serving you."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mrs. Bennet deigned not to make any reply, but, unable to contain' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'herself, began scolding one of her daughters.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Don''t keep coughing so, Kitty, for Heaven''s sake! Have a little' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'compassion on my nerves. You tear them to pieces."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Kitty has no discretion in her coughs," said her father; "she times' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'them ill."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"I do not cough for my own amusement," replied Kitty fretfully. "When is' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'your next ball to be, Lizzy?"' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"To-morrow fortnight."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Aye, so it is," cried her mother, "and Mrs. Long does not come back' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'till the day before; so it will be impossible for her to introduce him,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'for she will not know him herself."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Then, my dear, you may have the advantage of your friend, and introduce' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mr. Bingley to _her_."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Impossible, Mr. Bennet, impossible, when I am not acquainted with him' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'myself; how can you be so teasing?"' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"I honour your circumspection. A fortnight''s acquaintance is certainly' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'very little. One cannot know what a man really is by the end of a' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'fortnight. But if _we_ do not venture somebody else will; and after all,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mrs. Long and her daughters must stand their chance; and, therefore, as' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'she will think it an act of kindness, if you decline the office, I will' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'take it on myself."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'The girls stared at their father. Mrs. Bennet said only, "Nonsense,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'nonsense!"' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"What can be the meaning of that emphatic exclamation?" cried he. "Do' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'you consider the forms of introduction, and the stress that is laid on' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'them, as nonsense? I cannot quite agree with you _there_. What say you,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mary? For you are a young lady of deep reflection, I know, and read' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'great books and make extracts."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Mary wished to say something sensible, but knew not how.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"While Mary is adjusting her ideas," he continued, "let us return to Mr.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Bingley."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"I am sick of Mr. Bingley," cried his wife.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"I am sorry to hear _that_; but why did not you tell me that before? If' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'I had known as much this morning I certainly would not have called' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'on him. It is very unlucky; but as I have actually paid the visit, we' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'cannot escape the acquaintance now."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'The astonishment of the ladies was just what he wished; that of Mrs.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'Bennet perhaps surpassing the rest; though, when the first tumult of joy' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'was over, she began to declare that it was what she had expected all the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'while.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"How good it was in you, my dear Mr. Bennet! But I knew I should' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'persuade you at last. I was sure you loved your girls too well to' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'neglect such an acquaintance. Well, how pleased I am! and it is such a' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'good joke, too, that you should have gone this morning and never said a' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'word about it till now."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Now, Kitty, you may cough as much as you choose," said Mr. Bennet; and,' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'as he spoke, he left the room, fatigued with the raptures of his wife.' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"What an excellent father you have, girls!" said she, when the door was' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'shut. "I do not know how you will ever make him amends for his kindness;' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'or me, either, for that matter. At our time of life it is not so' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'pleasant, I can tell you, to be making new acquaintances every day; but' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'for your sakes, we would do anything. Lydia, my love, though you _are_' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'the youngest, I dare say Mr. Bingley will dance with you at the next' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'ball."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'"Oh!" said Lydia stoutly, "I am not afraid; for though I _am_ the' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'youngest, I''m the tallest."' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'The rest of the evening was spent in conjecturing how soon he would' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'return Mr. Bennet''s visit, and determining when they should ask him to' + NCHAR(13) + N'' + NCHAR(10) + N'dinner.');
